  {
    "chunk_id": "docling_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2010_Solutions_2010s_page_001_6",
    "text": "One way to see that this is optimal is to note that the common sum can never be less than n, since n itself belongs to one of the boxes. This implies that k ≤ (1 + ...+ n) /n = (n + 1)/2. Another argument is that if k > (n + 1)/2, then there would have to be two boxes with one number each (by the pigeonhole principle), but such boxes could not have the same sum.",
    "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
    "bbox": [
      0.12593984229104832,
      0.2875628212400565,
      0.4907111471405099,
      0.3881171341001161
    ],
    "page": "exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2010_Solutions_2010s_page_001",
    "order": 10
  },
  {
    "chunk_id": "docling_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2010_Solutions_2010s_page_001_20",
    "text": "A-5 We start with three lemmas.",
    "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
    "bbox": [
      0.5225563945758104,
      0.29067460310506227,
      0.7424812038076481,
      0.3038194443749034
    ],
    "page": "exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2010_Solutions_2010s_page_001",
    "order": 11
  },
  {
    "chunk_id": "docling_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2010_Solutions_2010s_page_001_21",
    "text": "Lemma 1. If x, y € G are nonzero orthogonal vectors, then *** is parallel to y.",
    "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
    "bbox": [
      0.5131578971644676,
      0.31540697699054715,
      0.9191729401572599,
      0.34449404757321006
    ],
    "page": "exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2010_Solutions_2010s_page_001",
    "order": 12
  },
  {
    "chunk_id": "docling_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2010_Solutions_2010s_page_001_22",
    "text": "Proof. Put z = xx y # 0, so that x, y, and Z = X*y are nonzero and mutually orthogonal. Then w = xx z # 0, so w = x*z is nonzero and orthogonal to x and z. However, if (x**) xy #0, then w = x*(x*y) = (x**) *y = (x**) x y is also orthogonal to y, a contradiction.",
    "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
    "bbox": [
      0.5169172954630405,
      0.3573878061595335,
      0.9210526271215861,
      0.43030753985633696
    ],
    "page": "exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2010_Solutions_2010s_page_001",
    "order": 13
  },
  {
    "chunk_id": "docling_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2010_Solutions_2010s_page_001_7",
    "text": "Remark. A much subtler question would be to find the smallest k (as a function of n) for which no such arrangement exists.",
    "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
    "bbox": [
      0.12781954970176249,
      0.39680232570554236,
      0.4906015101854555,
      0.4374999998058117
    ],
    "page": "exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2010_Solutions_2010s_page_001",
    "order": 14
  },
  {
    "chunk_id": "docling_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2010_Solutions_2010s_page_001_23",
    "text": "Lemma 2. If x € G is nonzero, and there exists y € G nonzero and orthogonal to x, then x** = 0.",
    "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
    "bbox": [
      0.5169172944574015,
      0.4418604649995998,
      0.9191729391516208,
      0.4694940475348716
    ],
    "page": "exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2010_Solutions_2010s_page_001",
    "order": 15
  },
  {
    "chunk_id": "docling_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2010_Solutions_2010s_page_001_8",
    "text": "A-2 The only such functions are those of the form f(x) = cx + d for some real numbers c,d (for which the property is obviously satisfied). To see this, suppose that f has the desired property. Then for any XE R,",
    "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
    "bbox": [
      0.0957894317810726,
      0.4485120769413133,
      0.4906754143483664,
      0.5058139535868827
    ],
    "page": "exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2010_Solutions_2010s_page_001",
    "order": 16
  },
  {
    "chunk_id": "docling_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2010_Solutions_2010s_page_001_24",
    "text": "Proof. Lemma 1 implies that x ** is parallel to both y and xx y, so it must be zero.",
    "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
    "bbox": [
      0.5169172953107689,
      0.485367063354714,
      0.9191729337384166,
      0.5131448410936005
    ],
    "page": "exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2010_Solutions_2010s_page_001",
    "order": 17
  },
  {
